00:41:58,220 --> 00:42:09,140
Traditional digital audio processing, like the MP3 files on your phone, or standard pitch correction software, relies on a mathematical tool called the short-time Fourier transform, or STFT.

812
00:42:09,380 --> 00:42:10,980
Okay, I actually know a bit about this.

813
00:42:11,060 --> 00:42:13,640
STFT has a massive built-in trade-off, right?

814
00:42:13,920 --> 00:42:14,300
It does.

815
00:42:14,380 --> 00:42:15,340
It's like a seesaw.

816
00:42:15,720 --> 00:42:24,940
If you want really high-frequency resolution, meaning you want to know the exact perfect pitch of a violin note, you have to sample a long stretch of audio.

817
00:42:25,080 --> 00:42:25,360
Yes.

818
00:42:25,360 --> 00:42:28,100
But by doing that, you lose time resolution.

819
00:42:28,300 --> 00:42:31,380
You lose the ability to pinpoint exactly when the note started.

820
00:42:31,860 --> 00:42:34,580
It is the fundamental time-frequency uncertainty relation.

821
00:42:35,180 --> 00:42:39,220
It is essentially the Heisenberg uncertainty principle applied to sound waves.

822
00:42:39,420 --> 00:42:39,640
Right.

823
00:42:40,040 --> 00:42:44,940
You can know the pitch perfectly, or you can know the timing perfectly, but you cannot know both at the same time.

824
00:42:45,100 --> 00:42:45,660
Exactly.

825
00:42:46,340 --> 00:42:52,680
If you optimize for pitch, the sharp, percussive attack of a snare drum gets smeared across time.

826
00:42:52,680 --> 00:42:57,400
But a paper claims this marine engine rejects the STFT completely.

827
00:42:57,640 --> 00:42:57,980
It does.

828
00:42:58,140 --> 00:43:00,460
It uses something called temporal interval counting.

829
00:43:01,120 --> 00:43:09,540
It tracks the exact microscopic intervals between the zero crossings of the raw sound wave to extract pitch, vibrato, and jitter instantly.

830
00:43:09,720 --> 00:43:10,420
That's the claim.

831
00:43:10,420 --> 00:43:12,840
Now, I have to stop and aggressively challenge this.

