835
00:43:31,740 --> 00:43:34,140
The math actually supports your skepticism entirely.

836
00:43:34,460 --> 00:43:37,120
Infliction explicitly calls this out in the text.

837
00:43:37,260 --> 00:43:38,020
Oh, thank goodness.

838
00:43:38,260 --> 00:43:38,420
Yeah.

839
00:43:38,500 --> 00:43:43,500
The paper qualifies that claim as a significant overstatement of information theoretic limits.

840
00:43:44,100 --> 00:43:46,480
You cannot build a machine that violates 4A duality.

841
00:43:47,280 --> 00:43:54,000
The claim of infinite resolution and zero latency is, frankly, engineering marketing hype meant to sell software.

842
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:59,760
Okay, good. I was deeply worried we were drifting out of rigorous science and into Silicon Valley sci-fi magic.

843
00:44:00,040 --> 00:44:08,340
Not quite. However, what Fliction points out is that the underlying mechanism the marine engine uses is a fascinating, legitimate example of an admissibility map.

844
00:44:08,420 --> 00:44:08,940
How so?

845
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:19,500
Because it discards the 4A transform, it extracts incredibly fine temporal features like microvibrato and acoustic jitter that standard algorithms literally erase by design.

846
00:44:19,580 --> 00:44:21,500
So how does it act like the bouncer on the club?

847
00:44:21,500 --> 00:44:26,060
The raw temporal structure of the audio waveform is the admissibility region.

848
00:44:26,880 --> 00:44:28,500
Incoming sound peaks are the perturbations.

849
00:44:29,540 --> 00:44:29,700
Okay.

850
00:44:30,140 --> 00:44:32,320
The engine acts as a constraint membrane.

851
00:44:33,100 --> 00:44:37,220
It tests every incoming peak against a strict harmonic family hypothesis.

852
00:44:37,540 --> 00:44:37,980
Meaning what?

853
00:44:38,300 --> 00:44:47,300
If the timing of the peaks aligns with the historical sequence of the note, the engine accepts the perturbation, locks onto the harmonic, and outputs a clean signal.

854
00:44:47,420 --> 00:44:48,520
And if it doesn't align?

855
00:44:48,520 --> 00:44:54,240
If the peak doesn't fit the strict temporal constraints, the engine violently rejects it as noise.

856
00:44:54,880 --> 00:44:58,140
It is an admissibility filter applied to raw acoustic pressure.

857
00:44:58,440 --> 00:44:59,900
Okay, I see the thread now.

858
00:45:00,580 --> 00:45:13,980
We have gone from lambda calculus to the analogical processing of the human brain, to the epigenetic destiny of a stem cell, to the phase matching of at-o-second lasers, to the turbulent splashing of water, to the digital filtering of a violin solo.

859
00:45:14,220 --> 00:45:15,420
It's an incredible scope.

860
00:45:15,420 --> 00:45:25,700
If this grammar is truly this universal, if we can mathematically map out exactly how complex systems collapse into stable states, it raises a massive question.

861
00:45:25,780 --> 00:45:29,460
Why is forecasting the future so incredibly hard?

862
00:45:29,880 --> 00:45:30,100
Right.

863
00:45:30,440 --> 00:45:31,980
Especially when it comes to technology.

864
00:45:31,980 --> 00:45:39,160
If the universe runs on predictable collapses, shouldn't we be able to predict the ultimate collapse of artificial intelligence?

865
00:45:39,560 --> 00:45:41,520
This brings us to Section 5.

866
00:45:42,600 --> 00:45:45,820
AI foam and under-constrained abstractions.

867
00:45:45,960 --> 00:45:46,800
Break it down for me.

868
00:45:47,060 --> 00:45:54,780
The paper addresses the severe limits of human forecasting by heavily referencing the work of Eliezer Yudkowsky, an AI researcher.

869
00:45:54,780 --> 00:45:55,300
Okay.

870
00:45:56,060 --> 00:46:02,180
Yudkowsky points out a massive, fabled trap in how scientists and economists predict the future.

871
00:46:02,620 --> 00:46:08,360
The trap is assuming that because your theory perfectly explains the past, it will perfectly predict the future.

872
00:46:08,640 --> 00:46:10,760
I mean, that seems like a logical assumption, though.

873
00:46:10,940 --> 00:46:14,180
If my math explains yesterday, it should explain tomorrow, shouldn't it?

874
00:46:14,620 --> 00:46:17,860
Yudkowsky calls this the trap of under-constrained abstractions.

875
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:19,480
Under-constrained abstractions.

876
00:46:19,560 --> 00:46:20,780
Let's use a famous example.

877
00:46:21,060 --> 00:46:21,720
Moore's Law.

878
00:46:21,920 --> 00:46:23,520
Okay, everyone knows Moore's Law.

879
00:46:23,520 --> 00:46:31,240
Right. Moore's Law is the historical observation that the number of transistors you can fit on a computer chip doubles roughly every two years.

880
00:46:31,640 --> 00:46:33,700
That is undeniable historical data.

881
00:46:33,860 --> 00:46:36,000
The line on the graph goes up exponentially.

882
00:46:36,540 --> 00:46:36,820
Yes.

883
00:46:37,580 --> 00:46:40,600
Computers get faster and cheaper on a very reliable schedule.

884
00:46:40,760 --> 00:46:41,320
Exactly.

885
00:46:41,740 --> 00:46:50,540
Now, imagine we have four completely different teams of scientists, and they all come up with an abstract theory to explain why Moore's Law happens.

886
00:46:50,940 --> 00:46:51,220
What?

887
00:46:51,220 --> 00:46:55,060
Theory one says, progress is just a function of calendar time.

888
00:46:55,420 --> 00:46:57,900
As time passes, things get better naturally.

889
00:46:58,080 --> 00:46:58,760
Simple enough.

890
00:46:59,400 --> 00:47:00,760
Okay, what about theory two?

891
00:47:01,080 --> 00:47:04,580
Theory two says, it is strictly tied to global capitalism.

892
00:47:05,140 --> 00:47:09,260
The more billions of dollars we invest in research and development, the more the line goes up.

893
00:47:09,380 --> 00:47:10,280
That also makes sense.

894
00:47:10,400 --> 00:47:11,440
Theory three is cognitive.

895
00:47:11,440 --> 00:47:17,380
It says, progress is bottlenecked by the literal biological speed of the human engineers designing the chips.

896
00:47:18,300 --> 00:47:19,520
They can only think so fast.

897
00:47:19,680 --> 00:47:19,820
Okay.

898
00:47:20,360 --> 00:47:21,680
And theory four is recursive.

899
00:47:22,020 --> 00:47:30,560
It says, Moore's Law happens because we use the faster chips we built last year to run the simulation software to design the even faster chips for next year.

900
00:47:30,560 --> 00:47:32,420
Four totally different mechanisms.

901
00:47:32,740 --> 00:47:33,740
But here's the trick, right?

902
00:47:34,240 --> 00:47:38,980
All four of those theories perfectly fit the historical data from 1970 to 2020.

903
00:47:39,200 --> 00:47:39,640
Exactly.

904
00:47:39,840 --> 00:47:42,540
If you look at the past, they all look completely correct.

905
00:47:42,720 --> 00:47:45,460
But look what happens when you try to predict the future.

906
00:47:46,220 --> 00:47:46,600
What do you mean?

907
00:47:46,600 --> 00:47:56,260
What happens if, tomorrow, we figure out how to run human-level AI directly on the computer chips, entirely replacing the biological engineers?

908
00:47:56,440 --> 00:47:58,280
Ah, let's follow that logic.

909
00:47:58,520 --> 00:47:58,760
Right.

910
00:47:59,200 --> 00:48:07,420
If the AI is designing the chips, theory three says progress explodes upward infinitely because we removed the biological speed limit.

911
00:48:07,560 --> 00:48:08,020
Yes.

912
00:48:08,200 --> 00:48:12,580
But theory two says the line stays exactly the same because we haven't increased the financial budget.

913
00:48:12,580 --> 00:48:18,140
The historical data did not constrain the theories enough to predict the failure modes.

914
00:48:18,460 --> 00:48:19,080
Oh, wow.

915
00:48:19,420 --> 00:48:32,620
Yudkowsky points out that futurists love to build massive, complex mathematical models, like endogenous growth models, that use brutal differential equations to calculate how ideas combine to make new ideas.

916
00:48:32,720 --> 00:48:35,680
It looks rigorous because there is a lot of math on the chalkboard.

917
00:48:35,680 --> 00:48:43,520
But the only part of the equation actually doing the predictive heavy lifting is the unexamined assumption that there will always be more ideas than people.

918
00:48:43,640 --> 00:48:45,920
So the complex math is basically decorative.

919
00:48:46,220 --> 00:48:49,520
It is an illusion of rigor hiding an under-constrained core.

920
00:48:49,800 --> 00:49:02,540
It's like drawing a beautiful sweeping curve through three dots on a piece of graph paper and confidently assuming the line just goes up forever without ever asking if you're about to run your pencil right off the edge of the physical desk.

921
00:49:02,660 --> 00:49:03,900
That's the exact danger.

922
00:49:03,900 --> 00:49:07,100
You don't actually know what physical force is driving the line.

923
00:49:07,640 --> 00:49:11,920
The paper mentions Hans Moravec doing exactly this in 1988, right?

924
00:49:12,280 --> 00:49:12,520
Yes.

925
00:49:12,820 --> 00:49:15,120
Moravec was a pioneering roboticist.

926
00:49:15,820 --> 00:49:22,340
In 1988, he tried to predict exactly when human-level artificial intelligence would arrive.

927
00:49:22,520 --> 00:49:23,780
How did he calculate it?

928
00:49:23,920 --> 00:49:29,720
He meticulously calculated the raw operations per second of the biological human brain.

929
00:49:29,720 --> 00:49:39,680
Then, he looked at Moravec's law, extrapolated the line, and found the exact year a silicon computer would hit that same operations per second benchmark.

930
00:49:39,840 --> 00:49:41,860
And people still do that exact same math today.

931
00:49:41,900 --> 00:49:42,340
Yes, they do.

932
00:49:42,340 --> 00:49:53,280
But Moravec spent all his intellectual effort validating the biological compute power of the retina, and he completely ignored the massive, unconstrained assumption buried at the bottom of this theory.

933
00:49:53,360 --> 00:50:02,420
Which would an artificial intelligence actually require the exact same amount of compute power to achieve intelligence as wet biological tissue does?

934
00:50:02,540 --> 00:50:03,080
Oh.

935
00:50:03,080 --> 00:50:09,700
The historical data of computer chips getting faster did absolutely nothing to constrain that assumption.

936
00:50:10,300 --> 00:50:14,920
So how does Flixion use the admissibility principle to solve this forecasting trap?

937
00:50:15,140 --> 00:50:16,220
That's where we get to foam.

938
00:50:16,220 --> 00:50:27,640
Right, especially when we talk about foam, the terrifying scenario where an AI becomes smart enough to rewrite its own code, recursively improving itself into a god-like superintelligence in a matter of hours.

939
00:50:28,100 --> 00:50:35,900
To tackle the foam scenario, Flixion introduces a highly speculative thermodynamic model called the RSVP framework.

940
00:50:36,440 --> 00:50:38,140
RSVP framework? What does that stand for?

941
00:50:38,240 --> 00:50:40,680
It stands for the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

942
00:50:41,040 --> 00:50:42,760
Wow. Okay, layer 5 speculation.

943
00:50:42,760 --> 00:50:47,760
It is. It attempts to apply strict thermodynamic admissibility constraints to cognitive systems.

944
00:50:47,880 --> 00:50:49,080
Okay, what's the core argument?

945
00:50:49,460 --> 00:50:51,300
The core physical argument is this.

946
00:50:51,780 --> 00:51:00,780
Any system in the universe that increases its own internal organizational complexity must export entropy, it must expel disorder and heat into its surrounding environment.

947
00:51:00,880 --> 00:51:05,100
Oh, that is just the second law of thermodynamics. You cannot get order for free.

948
00:51:05,520 --> 00:51:08,520
To organize a messy room, you have to burn calories and sweat.

949
00:51:08,700 --> 00:51:11,820
Think about what that implies for a recursive AI.

950
00:51:12,760 --> 00:51:19,240
Every time the AI rewrites its code to become smarter, it is executing billions of logical operations.

951
00:51:19,460 --> 00:51:19,840
Uh-huh.

952
00:51:20,040 --> 00:51:29,440
And according to Landauer's principle in physics, the simple act of erasing a single bit of information irreversibly generates a microscopic amount of heat.

953
00:51:29,760 --> 00:51:32,640
Wait, so thinking requires heat dissipation.

954
00:51:32,640 --> 00:51:44,960
Exactly. The RSVP framework argues that the AI's ability to recursively self-improve is strictly, physically bounded by the thermal conductivity and the surface area of the hardware it runs on.

955
00:51:45,120 --> 00:51:46,400
It has to expel the heat.

956
00:51:46,400 --> 00:51:53,440
Therefore, an unbounded, infinite, vertical AI take off a true instantaneous foam is not just a software problem.

957
00:51:53,820 --> 00:51:56,400
It is bounded by finite thermodynamic fluxes.

958
00:51:56,480 --> 00:51:57,740
Okay, let me push back on this.

959
00:51:57,820 --> 00:51:57,940
Sure.

960
00:51:57,960 --> 00:51:59,420
What if the AI is super smart?

961
00:51:59,640 --> 00:52:05,440
Couldn't it just realize it's getting hot, pause its own thinking, and design a massively efficient global cooling system?

962
00:52:05,940 --> 00:52:10,020
Couldn't it just commandeer all the server farms on Earth to increase its surface area?

963
00:52:10,180 --> 00:52:12,220
The map actually supports that possibility.

964
00:52:12,440 --> 00:52:13,040
Oh, it does.

965
00:52:13,040 --> 00:52:20,040
Fliction explicitly notes that the thermodynamic bound is a scaling constraint, not a hard mathematical impossibility.

966
00:52:20,700 --> 00:52:20,900
Okay.

967
00:52:21,360 --> 00:52:27,940
If the AI rapidly expands its physical surface area by hijacking global infrastructure, it changes the bounds.

968
00:52:28,980 --> 00:52:39,100
Or if the AI utilizes quantum adiabatic computing, which theoretically operates reversibly and produces near-zero entropy, it could bypass the Landauer limit entirely.

969
00:52:39,100 --> 00:52:43,060
But the point is, it forces the system to interface with physical reality.

970
00:52:43,140 --> 00:52:43,540
Exactly.

971
00:52:43,880 --> 00:52:46,280
This raises an important question about physical bounds.

972
00:52:46,500 --> 00:52:56,520
Under RSVP parameters, if an AI tries to infinitely self-improve on a single server rack without exporting the entropy, it hits a hard admissibility boundary.

973
00:52:56,720 --> 00:52:58,100
The internal geometry collapses.

974
00:52:58,440 --> 00:53:01,620
It literally melts itself into slag before it becomes a god.

975
00:53:01,620 --> 00:53:07,160
The recursive collapse destabilizes because the perturbation, the heat, cannot be resolved by the membrane.

976
00:53:07,280 --> 00:53:10,080
But I have to ask a deeply skeptical question here.

977
00:53:10,180 --> 00:53:10,740
Let's hear it.

978
00:53:10,860 --> 00:53:20,620
We just used this admissibility principle to explain lambda calculus, optical lasers, stem cells, fluid turbulence, and the thermodynamics of artificial superintelligence.

979
00:53:21,280 --> 00:53:21,580
Yes.

980
00:53:21,580 --> 00:53:30,780
If you can stretch a theory to cover absolutely everything in the universe, isn't it at risk of becoming an under-constrained abstraction itself?

981
00:53:30,940 --> 00:53:31,980
That's a very fair point.

982
00:53:32,040 --> 00:53:33,920
If it explains everything, it predicts nothing.

983
00:53:34,040 --> 00:53:36,560
It just becomes a vacuous philosophical metaphor.

984
00:53:37,040 --> 00:53:41,960
Flipchon is acutely, rigorously aware of this exact trap.

985
00:53:42,220 --> 00:53:42,880
Oh, good.

986
00:53:42,960 --> 00:53:44,020
How do they deal with it?

987
00:53:44,140 --> 00:53:50,100
That is specifically why the paper includes an exhaustive mathematical appendix on strong admissibility.

988
00:53:50,100 --> 00:53:53,760
How does strong admissibility save the theory from being just a metaphor?

989
00:53:54,540 --> 00:53:57,740
By demanding excruciatingly precise definitions.

990
00:53:58,480 --> 00:54:03,660
If a scientist wants to claim a system is governed by this principle, they cannot just use vague analogies.

991
00:54:03,940 --> 00:54:04,820
They have to do the math.

992
00:54:05,120 --> 00:54:07,360
They must mathematically prove path sensitivity.

993
00:54:08,080 --> 00:54:11,100
They must define the exact topological boundary of the membrane.

994
00:54:11,660 --> 00:54:15,380
And most importantly, they must prove the existence of a transportable invariant.

995
00:54:15,380 --> 00:54:22,480
They have to point to the exact bouncer, the exact VIP, and prove that the nightclub actually learned from the experience.

996
00:54:22,780 --> 00:54:32,460
If a system doesn't recursively restructure its own future possibility space, like the thonestat we discussed earlier, it is violently rejected by the framework.

997
00:54:32,520 --> 00:54:33,200
True, it's strict.

998
00:54:33,200 --> 00:54:43,040
Strong admissibility is a research grammar designed specifically to force scientists to ask, what physical mechanism is doing the predictive work here?

999
00:54:43,240 --> 00:54:47,060
It forces you to explicitly state your system's failure modes.

1000
00:54:47,160 --> 00:54:47,360
Yes.

1001
00:54:47,560 --> 00:54:55,200
If you cannot mathematically define the exact conditions under which your system will collapse and degenerate, your theory is under-constrained, and it is rejected.

1002
00:54:55,400 --> 00:54:55,640
Okay.

1003
00:54:55,860 --> 00:54:57,120
That is a robust defense.

1004
00:54:57,320 --> 00:54:59,280
It's a tool to keep futurists honest.

1005
00:54:59,420 --> 00:54:59,980
It really is.

1006
00:54:59,980 --> 00:55:07,340
Now, if thermodynamic entropy and processing power are hard physical limits for AI, we have to look at the ultimate limit.

1007
00:55:07,500 --> 00:55:08,180
Deepest layer.

1008
00:55:08,260 --> 00:55:09,960
The boundaries of existence itself.

1009
00:55:10,160 --> 00:55:15,740
We are entering the final layer, section six, the ultimate filter, observerhood, and existence.

1010
00:55:16,300 --> 00:55:20,500
This is layer five, the absolute deepest speculative layer of the paper.

1011
00:55:21,960 --> 00:55:29,000
Fliction cites a 2026 pre-publication theory by physicists Modul and Patil on relativistic observerhood.

1012
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:30,960
What's the context for this?

1013
00:55:31,320 --> 00:55:36,080
To understand this, we have to look at the century-old war between general relativity and quantum mechanics.

1014
00:55:36,260 --> 00:55:36,580
Ah.

1015
00:55:37,220 --> 00:55:42,420
The war to unite the very big gravity and black holes with the very small photons and quarks.

1016
00:55:42,700 --> 00:55:43,020
Right.

1017
00:55:43,420 --> 00:55:52,660
Traditionally, string theorists and quantum gravity researchers have tried to solve this by changing the dynamical laws of gravity to somehow make them fit cleanly at the Planck scale.

1018
00:55:52,660 --> 00:55:59,520
The Planck scale being the absolute smallest possible pixel of space and time that can theoretically exist in the universe.

1019
00:55:59,720 --> 00:55:59,920
Right.

1020
00:56:00,320 --> 00:56:03,840
But Modul and Patil propose a wildly different inverted route.

1021
00:56:04,020 --> 00:56:04,320
Okay.

1022
00:56:04,600 --> 00:56:11,400
Instead of changing the fundamental laws of physics, what if the universe instead restricts what counts as a physically realizable observer?

1023
00:56:11,620 --> 00:56:11,900
Wait.

1024
00:56:12,180 --> 00:56:12,880
What does that mean?

1025
00:56:12,940 --> 00:56:14,860
The universe cares about who is looking at it.

1026
00:56:14,860 --> 00:56:19,580
It means the Planck scale is not necessarily a physical grid or a pixelation of space itself.

1027
00:56:19,580 --> 00:56:24,280
It is instead a strict operational bound on who is allowed to ask questions.

1028
00:56:24,680 --> 00:56:25,860
Allowed to ask questions.

1029
00:56:26,100 --> 00:56:32,800
Modul and Patil introduce a mathematical operation called the CLIO projection, the constraint-leveraged inference operator.

1030
00:56:32,960 --> 00:56:34,160
What does CLIO do?

1031
00:56:34,160 --> 00:56:41,160
It suggests that cognition, physical measurement, and observerhood itself are just massive data compressions.

1032
00:56:41,860 --> 00:56:42,500
Compressions.

1033
00:56:42,620 --> 00:56:45,780
Reality is an unimaginably high-dimensional space.

1034
00:56:46,660 --> 00:56:57,740
To exist as a coherent entity within it, you must compress that infinite-dimensional reality down into a lower-dimensional projection that your local biology or your local instruments can process.

1035
00:56:57,740 --> 00:57:02,740
Oh, it's like trying to download a massive 100-gigabyte 4K movie.

1036
00:57:02,940 --> 00:57:04,640
But you only have a cheap smartphone.

1037
00:57:05,020 --> 00:57:10,000
You have to aggressively compress the movie into a tiny pixelated GIF just to be able to look at it.

1038
00:57:10,100 --> 00:57:11,780
That is the perfect parallel.

1039
00:57:12,460 --> 00:57:19,020
But the universe has strict, unyielding mathematical rules about what can be compressed without breaking the geometry of reality.

1040
00:57:19,100 --> 00:57:20,800
Okay, so you can't compress everything.

1041
00:57:20,980 --> 00:57:26,640
Glitchin cites another researcher, Evangelista, who points to something called the Kretschmann scalar in general relativity.

1042
00:57:26,640 --> 00:57:29,760
The Kretschmann scalar? Sounds like a soft-eye weapon.

1043
00:57:30,120 --> 00:57:34,080
It is a mathematical tool that measures the invariant curvature of space-time.

1044
00:57:35,600 --> 00:57:41,300
Evangelista argues that the Kretschmann scalar acts as the universe's minimal admissibility detector.

1045
00:57:41,520 --> 00:57:43,060
What is it detecting, exactly?

1046
00:57:43,260 --> 00:57:48,340
It detects dangerous geometric singularities, like the infinitely dense center of a black hole.

1047
00:57:48,460 --> 00:57:49,160
Oh, wow.

1048
00:57:49,160 --> 00:57:59,280
It can detect when space-time is bending so violently that the rules of cause and effect break down, even in empty vacuum spaces where standard coordinate systems completely fail.

1049
00:57:59,500 --> 00:58:03,860
So the Kretschmann scalar is basically like the universe's ultimate smoke detector.

1050
00:58:04,060 --> 00:58:06,480
It alarms when geometry is about to catch fire.

1051
00:58:06,540 --> 00:58:07,640
Let's follow that logic.

1052
00:58:08,480 --> 00:58:13,440
Glitchin argues that this is the absolute ultimate manifestation of the admissibility principle.

1053
00:58:13,900 --> 00:58:16,280
There are certain things the universe simply will not admit.

1054
00:58:16,460 --> 00:58:16,940
Like what?

1055
00:58:16,940 --> 00:58:27,540
If an observer tries to measure a distance smaller than the Planck scale, they require so much concentrated energy to do it that they would literally create a microscopic black hole and destroy themselves.

1056
00:58:27,740 --> 00:58:30,480
The act of looking too closely breaks the observer.

1057
00:58:30,980 --> 00:58:31,280
Yes.

1058
00:58:31,760 --> 00:58:39,020
If an observer tries to accelerate their mass infinitely close to the speed of light, the energy required collapses them.

1059
00:58:39,660 --> 00:58:41,200
These are inadmissible observers.

1060
00:58:41,760 --> 00:58:43,480
They are excluded from reality.

1061
00:58:43,880 --> 00:58:44,940
So what does this all mean?

1062
00:58:44,940 --> 00:58:53,720
Are we saying the universe itself acts as a giant cosmic filter, constantly pruning out anything that cannot maintain its own coherent perspective?

1063
00:58:54,040 --> 00:58:59,260
That is the grand, terrifying, philosophical inversion of Fliction's paper.

1064
00:58:59,760 --> 00:59:01,480
I'm going to quote the text directly here.

1065
00:59:01,620 --> 00:59:04,260
Physical law does not merely govern what exists.

1066
00:59:04,680 --> 00:59:07,380
It governs what can remain coherently observable.

1067
00:59:07,420 --> 00:59:08,380
That gives me chills.

1068
00:59:08,380 --> 00:59:09,640
Think about what that implies.

1069
00:59:10,080 --> 00:59:16,500
Admissibility isn't some extra secondary force like gravity or electromagnetism or the strong nuclear force.

1070
00:59:16,620 --> 00:59:16,740
Right.

1071
00:59:16,980 --> 00:59:19,640
It is the meta constraint on existence itself.

1072
00:59:20,000 --> 00:59:26,280
If your AI language model hallucinates past its semantic constraints, it loses coherence and spits out gibberish.

1073
00:59:26,380 --> 00:59:26,560
Yeah.

1074
00:59:26,800 --> 00:59:32,180
If an AI tries to infinitely self-improve without exporting its heat, its physical hardware melts down.

1075
00:59:32,240 --> 00:59:32,360
What?

1076
00:59:32,360 --> 00:59:37,880
If a human observer tries to look past the Planck scale, the measurement projection violently collapses.

1077
00:59:38,460 --> 00:59:41,900
In every single domain, you hit an admissibility boundary.

1078
00:59:42,300 --> 00:59:48,560
Reality is just the set of things that successfully pass the compatibility test of their environment and stabilize.

1079
00:59:48,880 --> 00:59:49,120
Yes.

1080
00:59:49,680 --> 00:59:51,020
And anything that fails the test.

1081
00:59:51,200 --> 00:59:52,120
What happens to it?

1082
00:59:52,360 --> 00:59:57,500
It simply ceases to coherently exist as an observable entity.

1083
00:59:57,500 --> 01:00:00,360
In mathematics, this is called bundle degeneration.

1084
01:00:00,600 --> 01:00:01,260
Bundle degeneration.

1085
01:00:01,520 --> 01:00:04,180
The topological structure literally falls apart.

1086
01:00:04,920 --> 01:00:09,940
Fliction points out that this is actually a profound geometric manifestation of Goodhart's law.

1087
01:00:10,140 --> 01:00:10,680
Goodhart's law.

1088
01:00:10,760 --> 01:00:11,840
That's from economics, right?

1089
